com.google.enterprise.connector.spi
Interface DocumentList

All Superinterfaces:
com.google.enterprise.connector.spiimpl.Document, com.google.enterprise.connector.spiimpl.DocumentListImpl
public interface DocumentList
extends com.google.enterprise.connector.spiimpl.DocumentListImpl

Interface that represents a list of documents to be traversed. This type is the return type of TraversalManager.startTraversal() and resumeTraversal().

This single interface can be thought of as representing a list of documents, each of which is a list of properties, each of which is a list of values. Iteration is provided through each object via nextXXX(), similar to the "cursor" concept of java.sql.ResultSet. By analogy, we can say that an object implementing this interface contains three "cursors": a "document cursor", a "property cursor" and a "value cursor". Thus, a consumer might traverse as follows: 

 DocumentList docList = ...
 while (docList.nextDocument()) {
   while (docList.nextProperty()) {
     while (docList.nextValue()) {
       Value v = docList.getValue();
     }
   }
 }
There are two additions to this pattern:
  1. A property has a name, accessed by getPropertyName()
  2. Properties can be accessed by name, using findProperty(String name)
Thus, to look at a particular named property specially, the consumer can call findProperty(String name) for that name. Subsequent calls to nextValue() and getValue will then apply to the Values of that property. However, a call to findProperty(String name) does not advance the property cursor. Subsequent calls to nextProperty() advance the property cursor exactly as though findProperty(String name) had not been called.

In practice the consumer is expected to call findProperty(String name) for certain named properties of interest and then to iterate through all the properties by calls to nextProperty(), as follows: 

 DocumentList docList = ...
 while (docList.nextDocument()) {
   if (findProperty(special1)) {
      // do something special with this special property's values
   }
   if (findProperty(special2)) {
      // similar...
   }
   while (docList.nextProperty()) {
     String propertyName = docList.getPropertyName();
     // in this loop it is expected to re-encounter  
     // the special properties dealt with earlier
     while (docList.nextValue()) {
       Value v = docList.getValue();
       // do something...
     }
   }
 }
The data of a property is carried by the Value type.

All of the methods of this interface may throw a RepositoryException, since any of them may be implemented by a call to a foreign repository that may itself throw an exception.

Method Detail

nextDocument

public boolean nextDocument()
Moves the document cursor down one row from its current position. The document cursor is initially positioned before the first document; the first call to the method nextDocument makes the first document the current document; the second call makes the second document the current document, and so on. In addition, after each call to nextDocument, the property cursor is positioned before the first property for the current document.

Specified by:
nextDocument in interface com.google.enterprise.connector.spiimpl.DocumentListImpl
Returns:
true if the new current document is valid; false if there are no more documents

In addition, after each call to nextProperty, the value cursor is positioned before the first value for the current property.

findProperty

public boolean findProperty(java.lang.String name)
Finds a property by name. If the current document has a property with that name, then it becomes the current property: that is, subsequent calls to nextValue and getValue will be with respect to the named property. However, the property cursor is not advanced. A subsequent call to nextProperty will advance the property cursor in exactly the same way as if findProperty had not been called.

Specified by:
findProperty in interface com.google.enterprise.connector.spiimpl.Document
Parameters:
name - The name of the property to find
Returns:
true if the new current document has a valid property with the requested name; false if not

checkpoint

public java.lang.String checkpoint()
                            throws RepositoryException
Checkpoints the traversal process. The caller may call this at any time during consumption of the document list. By calling this method, the caller indicates that it has successfully processed all the documents up to and including the document cursor. The caller need not consume the entire document list - the caller may consume as much or as little as it chooses. If the implementation wants the caller to persist the traversal state, then it should write a string representation of that state and return it. If the implementation prefers to maintain state itself, it should use this call as a signal to commit its state, up to the document before the document at the document cursor.

Specified by:
checkpoint in interface com.google.enterprise.connector.spiimpl.Document
Returns:
A string that can be used by a subsequent call to the TraversalManager.resumeTraversal(String) method.
Throws:
RepositoryException
